# Wikimyei Config Keys

`src/config/.config` section: `[WIKIMYEI]`

The Wikimyei section binds authored DSL, net, and feature files into the
graph-first protocol bundle. These paths are part of deterministic protocol
construction. Conventional grammar paths are derived from the paired data paths
under `src/config/grammar`; author explicit `*_bnf_path` keys only for
nonstandard grammar overrides.

## Observer Belief

- `wikimyei_observer_belief_dsl_path`
  - Default grammar: `grammar/wikimyei.observer.belief.dsl.bnf`.
  - Deterministic observer contract that converts Channel MDN NodeLift
    potential distributions into NodeLift-aware allocation belief semantics.
  - V1 requires feature semantics from the Ujcamei kline registry/dock
    coordinate space, numeraire-relative NodeLift projection,
    arithmetic-return scenarios, and an accounting numeraire supplied as a
    graph node by `BasePolicy`.
  - The DSL must keep `PROJECTION_VALIDATION_REQUIRED = true` and
    `LIVE_CAPITAL_ALLOWED = false` until projected NodeLift returns have an
    empirical validation artifact.

## Spot Distributional Utility Policy

- `wikimyei_policy_portfolio_spot_distributional_utility_dsl_path`
  - Default grammar:
    `grammar/wikimyei.policy.portfolio.spot_distributional_utility.dsl.bnf`.
  - Deterministic portfolio policy contract for the first allocation method.
  - V1 consumes only post-projection `AllocationBelief`, is long-only and
    spot-only, uses projected-gradient search over unified graph-node target
    weights, and requires the accounting numeraire to be included in that
    target-node universe.
  - The policy DSL mirrors the observer safety flags:
    `PROJECTION_VALIDATION_REQUIRED = true` and `LIVE_CAPITAL_ALLOWED = false`.

## Graph Node Allocation Policy

- `wikimyei_policy_portfolio_graph_node_allocation_dsl_path`
  - Default grammar:
    `grammar/wikimyei.policy.portfolio.graph_node_allocation.dsl.bnf`.
  - Contract-only trainable policy surface for future graph-node allocation policies.
  - V1 consumes `kikijyeba.environment.policy_input.v1` and emits
    `kikijyeba.environment.action.target_node_weights.v1` through
    `target_node_weights_simplex.v1`.
  - `ACTION_DISTRIBUTION = masked_dirichlet_simplex.v1` is the default
    PPO stochastic action law. `masked_logistic_normal_simplex.v1` is
    accepted as a contract candidate, but is not the default.
  - The accounting numeraire remains an ordinary graph node inside the same
    target-node weight vector; there is no separate cash output.
  - `RAW_MDN_INPUT_ALLOWED = false`, `PPO_IMPLEMENTED = true`, and
    `LIVE_CAPITAL_ALLOWED = false` are required. PPO V0 is Runtime-owned and
    replay/paper-only.
  - Runtime `ppo_policy_artifact_contract.v1` gates executable PPO-shaped
    policy facts. Pre-execution contracts require actor/critic architecture
    digests and GAE identity; the graph-node allocation `.jkimyei` owns stable
    PPO hyperparameters and the seed. Runtime-emitted
    actor/critic checkpoint, optimizer-state, rollout collection, PPO update
    report, validation rollout report, and policy-quality report digests are
    bound after Runtime writes those artifacts. Runtime derives policy source
    and action-distribution config digests from configured graph-node
    allocation files, derives PPO contract fields from the `.jkimyei`, and
    derives the PPO config digest from bound PPO V0 hyperparameters when the
    full digest input set is present.
- `wikimyei_policy_portfolio_graph_node_allocation_net_path`
  - Default grammar:
    `grammar/wikimyei.policy.portfolio.graph_node_allocation.net.bnf`.
  - Architecture identity for the bounded PPO V0 graph-node allocation policy.
    V1 binds the feature manifest, node/global/risk encoder shape,
    mask-aware pooling, `node_weight_logits` policy head, `state_value` critic
    head, Dirichlet default distribution config, and logistic-normal candidate
    config. The net decoder derives the V1 action adapter/distribution and PPO
    execution gate from the policy surface, and derives input feature dimensions
    from the feature manifest contract. Raw timestamp and anchor identity stay
    outside the actor-visible global feature tensor.
- `wikimyei_policy_portfolio_graph_node_allocation_features_path`
  - Default grammar:
    `grammar/wikimyei.policy.portfolio.graph_node_allocation.features.dsl.bnf`.
  - Actor-feature manifest for the graph-node allocation policy. It freezes
    the actor-visible node/global/risk feature names used by
    `kikijyeba.environment.policy_input.v1`; the decoder derives feature
    dimensions from those lists and treats authored dimension fields as optional
    assertions. Raw MDN tensors and the full scenario bank remain forbidden for
    V1.

`src/config/.config` section: `[JKIMYEI]`

- `wikimyei_representation_mtf_jepa_mae_vicreg_jkimyei_path`
  - Default grammar:
    `grammar/wikimyei.representation.mtf_jepa_mae_vicreg.jkimyei.bnf`.
  - Experimental MTF-JEPA-MAE-VICReg training profile. In addition to
    JEPA/MAE masking and launcher-owned augmentation, it owns the two
    model-internal weak-view controls used only by the VICReg branch.
  - `VICREG_VIEW_GAUSSIAN_JITTER_STD` is finite and non-negative; its
    backward-compatible default is `0.005`.
  - `VICREG_VIEW_TIME_DROPOUT_SCALE` is in `[0,1]`; its backward-compatible
    default is `0.10`. The effective time-drop probability is
    `min(0.10, MASK_RATIO_TIME * VICREG_VIEW_TIME_DROPOUT_SCALE)`.
  - Setting both fields to `0.0` disables those two effects but does not
    disable launcher-owned augmentation or weak-view feature drop derived from
    `MASK_RATIO_CHANNEL`. Both authored controls are part of protocol identity;
    reports also persist the resolved effective time-drop probability.
- `wikimyei_inference_expected_value_mdn_jkimyei_path`
  - Default grammar:
    `grammar/wikimyei.inference.expected_value.mdn.jkimyei.bnf`.
  - Channel-context MDN training profile. It requires
    `TASK = channel_inference_mdn` and owns optimizer/report cadence plus
    forecast-side training losses.
  - Edge-return objective controls are training settings, not network-shape
    settings. `MDN_EDGE_RETURN_AUXILIARY_*` applies auxiliary base-minus-quote
    losses to the node-potential expected-value projection.
    `MDN_DIRECT_EDGE_RETURN_READOUT_*` enables and weights the dedicated direct
    edge-return readout head. The direct-readout target scale is loss-only;
    metrics stay in raw return space. The direct-readout warmup fields can
    override the NLL weight and optionally train only the direct edge head during
    the configured warmup window. The post-warmup NLL weight controls whether
    ordinary MDN NLL competition returns after that window. The identity-mode
    fields select the explicit direct-readout ablation surface (`shared`,
    `edge_embedding`, `per_edge`, or `edge_embedding_per_edge`), the configured
    base-edge count, the optional edge embedding width, and the optional
    residual adapter hidden width. These controls intentionally live in
    `.jkimyei` so benchmark training runs can name the intervention without
    changing the base `.net` definition.
    Non-MDN `.jkimyei` profiles must leave these fields disabled/zero or
    neutral.
- `wikimyei_policy_portfolio_graph_node_allocation_jkimyei_path`
  - Default grammar:
    `grammar/wikimyei.policy.portfolio.graph_node_allocation.jkimyei.bnf`.
  - Bounded PPO V0 policy-training profile. It requires
    `TASK = policy_graph_node_allocation_ppo_v0`; the training-spec decoder
    derives the fixed PPO optimizer, causal schedule requirement, PPO execution
    gate, and checkpoint kind from the task, and live capital remains forbidden
    by the policy DSL and Runtime authority.

All trainable component `.jkimyei` grammars keep only component training knobs.
The current canonical no-lookahead/order contract block is
`NO_LOOKAHEAD_CONTRACT` in `src/config/kikijyeba.protocol.cwu_02v.dsl`;
that block authors `CONTRACT_ID`, while config-bundle loading derives the
no-lookahead contract digest from a canonical serialization of the block. It
then derives no-lookahead ids, digests, component roles, and serving-order
indexes from that protocol contract, and component assembly ids from the owning
component DSLs, before validating training specs. The training-spec decoder also
derives each training version token, freeze policy, and policy-task causal/PPO
checkpoint gate from `TASK` and fills the canonical v1 visibility, lane,
valid-from, and artifact-provenance policies when those fields are omitted from
root `.jkimyei` profiles. Runtime
carries the derived policy `.jkimyei` contract refs into policy-training
evidence, and Lattice fails readiness-grade
claims closed when those refs are missing or drift from the canonical cwu_02v
no-lookahead contract. Policy-training `accounting_numeraire_node_id` is derived
from `[ACCOUNTING].accounting_numeraire_node_id`; `target_node_ids` are derived
from `src/config/kikijyeba.topology.graph.dsl`; `target_node_universe_digest` is
derived from the graph/accounting pair; policy input/action/reward surface
values, policy-source identity digests, and action-distribution config digest
are derived from
`src/config/wikimyei.policy.portfolio.graph_node_allocation.dsl`, the
configured graph-node allocation net, the feature manifest, derived manifest
feature dimensions, and the configured policy `.jkimyei`; none of these are
authored in checked-in activation config, including `training_config_digest`;
policy
id/kind, training-schedule mode, causal schedule digest, snapshot-family digest,
and selector policy digests are derived from the selected policy-training
Runtime wave. If the
active config wave is not policy training, Runtime uses the unique
policy-training `WAVE_SETTINGS` block in the same catalog and fails closed when
that selection is ambiguous. Runtime derives the policy operator-surface and
component-assembly fingerprint from the effective policy-training contract
instead of accepting the checked-in contract as the source. Protocol-contract
and graph-order fingerprints are derived from the configured graph-first
protocol bundle; when `replay_job_dir` is present, Runtime derives the resolved
`source_cursor_token`, replay-report policy/profile identity,
parent allocation/replay report digests, and replay-artifact identity locks from
the completed replay job, including digest-bound replay reports under configured
Runtime roots, plus representation/MDN bundle checkpoint and generation-vector
inputs from the replay forecast fact. Runtime also derives the PPO
hyperparameter fields, minibatch size, max-gradient norm, policy-training
`max_steps`, and random seed from the configured graph-node allocation
`.jkimyei`, derives
`linear_transaction_cost_rate` and policy-training `max_parallel_jobs` from the
configured Environment rollout profile, derives `initial_equity_numeraire`,
`max_node_weight`, and `max_turnover_l1` from the configured Environment replay
contract,
derives `ppo_config_digest` from bound PPO V0 hyperparameters when the full
digest input set is present, derives fresh-spawn parent policy seed lineage
from `resume_mode=fresh_spawn`, and derives the PPO advantage-normalization
policy from Runtime PPO update semantics. Runtime dry-runs derive PPO V0
activation from the selected wave, split policy, configured policy profile, and
completed compatible replay artifacts; execute still requires a materialized
proof contract or handoff carrying policy-execution no-lookahead locks.
Policy-training Runtime waves bind `TRAIN_SPLIT`,
`VALIDATION_SPLIT`, and `TEST_SPLIT`; Runtime derives the split-policy
fingerprint plus the training/validation/test semantic range digests from those
names and `[UJCAMEI].ujcamei_source_splits_dsl_path` bound to
`[HERO].lattice_split_policy_dsl_path`. Runtime derives
`normalization_fit_range_digest` and `replay_buffer_source_range_digest` from
`training_range_digest`, and policy-execution parent replay input mirrors from
the parent replay environment identity. Runtime derives the policy-execution
target anchor range from `validation_range_digest`, defaults an omitted embargo
purged window from that target range, derives the Runtime-owned purged-embargo
policy fingerprint, derives policy-execution target id,
consumed artifact lists from policy-execution input locks and
consumed checkpoint lists from bundle checkpoint inputs, consumed
generation-vector lists from bundle generation inputs and replay forecast
lineage while parent policy generation-vector lineage remains in its dedicated
field, and trained-against bundle generation
mirrors from representation/MDN bundle inputs. Runtime also
derives
policy output fit/valid-from anchor mirrors from the policy-execution target
range, and representation/MDN bundle component ids from the active protocol. The
contract protocol id is derived from the active protocol when
`config_path` is present and fills default schema/job-kind, action-distribution,
resume-mode, causal schedule, cursor-key, and selector-split values from Runtime
policy-training defaults.
Graph-node policy `.jkimyei` and `.net` authoring omit `ACTION_DISTRIBUTION`;
the policy DSL owns that identity, and the net decoder derives the matching V1
defaults. Root `.jkimyei` profiles also omit runtime model-state input
checkpoint fields; Marshal/Runtime handoffs own concrete checkpoint paths.

These observer and policy assemblies are included in the graph-first
`wikimyei_registry` and dock-binding report. Lattice can audit their identity
and dock compatibility, but execution authority remains outside Lattice.
